I thought the whole point of giving Web merchants all that credit card
information (expiration date, the code number of the back, etc.) was so
they could get a purchase approved _before_ they processed it.
Apparently not.

For some as-yet unknown reason (perhaps the purchase of the Radiohead
album, which was denominated in pounds sterling), HSBC put a hold on my
credit card. (And I can't get it lifted until tomorrow, because only the
fraud unit can lift it and they don't work weekends. Grrrr!)

Yet purchases from Drugstore.com and Amazon went through and _produced
confirmations_, only to generate e-mail later saying there was a problem
with payment. Shouldn't they have rejected the transaction at the time I
made it?

Also, fuck HSBC for not notifying me of the hold. They send me e-mails
for every other fucking thing I or they do on the account. But a hold,
that they don't think is important enough to tell me about.

And I absolutely hate that all these kind of things happen on weekends,
so I have to wait until Monday to resolve them, while in the meantime my
blood pressure spikes.

