There are a couple of brands of &quot;banks&quot; here that offer this.  At one
point I was considering a Manulife &quot;One&quot; mortgage.  It is supposed to
replace all of your bank accounts with a single line of credit based
on your mortgage.  You can split the account into up to ten
subaccounts and the statements track the interest and other charges
separately for each of the sub-accounts.  you can lock in an interest
rate on a portion of the debt in one of the subaccounts if you fear
rising interest rates.  I believe that they have a credit card
attached to it.

Charges immediately start accruing interest.  Payments, including
payroll payments, immediately reduce your mortgage interest.  If you
get paid on the 15th and make buy a plane ticket or something on the
22nd, then you've saved a week's interest on that money.  At debt
rates of interest, rather than savings rates.

Next question:  What do the US call &quot;Prime Rate&quot;?
I'm not sure what the US term is that corresponds to the Canadian
&quot;prime&quot; loan interest rate.  HELOCs like this typically charge &quot;prime&quot;
interest, which is currently 6.25% at my bank.  The big banks all set
their own prime rate, but usually match each other.  My own Heloc is
also at prime.  My separate mortgage, floating but inflexible, is at
prime minus 0.65%.  My non-HE LOC is prime plus 2.5%  My margin at one
broker would be prime, if I chose to use it.  My margin at my main
broker, should I bother to set it up, would be at prime plus 2%.

I suspect that Americans must not use the concept of a bank's &quot;prime
rate&quot; because of the terminology &quot;sub-prime&quot;.  In Canada, a
&quot;sub-prime&quot; mortgage is a good one, not a bad one.  Only the bad risks
pay more than prime.
