In double-entry accounting, every entry needs to have matching entries
in a &quot;debit&quot; account and a &quot;credit&quot; account.  Those of us with a
science background like to think of debit as &quot;positive&quot; and credit as
&quot;negative&quot; though I bet the finance geeks in the audience are
shuddering.  Just like physics, accounting has conservation rules, and
debits and credits must always sum to zero.

Until you mentioned that, I never noticed (or had forgotten noticing)
that &quot;Debt&quot; and &quot;Debit&quot; are obviously closely related.

Anyhow, from THE BANK'S point of view, your account is a debit, and
their debt.  Your credit card is money that's due to them.  The
context shift from bank to customer while keeping the name &quot;credit
card&quot; leads to some confusion.

Anyhow, I should start thinking of &quot;debit/credit&quot; instead of
&quot;positive/negative&quot;, and be careful not to diss finance geeks.  I
enter school the day after New Years, studying to become one.
